---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Methodology — guitarserials.org" description="How guitarserials.org decodes serial numbers and assigns confidence tiers.">
  <div class="prose max-w-2xl py-8 dark:prose-invert">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Methodology</h1>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Confidence tiers</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">
      Every decode is assigned one of six tiers. The tier combines (a) how definitive the serial
      format itself is and (b) how the decoded year compares to any year you provide.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6 text-sm text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">
      <li><strong>verified</strong> — observationally confirmed against ground-truth data.</li>
      <li><strong>high</strong> — format is definitive or the decoded year is within 1 year of the listing context.</li>
      <li><strong>hybrid</strong> — multiple structurally valid interpretations; the best was picked by year proximity.</li>
      <li><strong>medium</strong> — short-numeric formats (bridge-plate, pre-1961 stamp) with a strong model hint.</li>
      <li><strong>low</strong> — reserved; not currently emitted.</li>
      <li><strong>review</strong> — decoded year is 2-5 years off the listing context; plausible but worth a human look.</li>
      <li><strong>rejected</strong> — decoded year is more than 5 years off; probably stock-photo or OCR contamination.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Year cross-validation</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">
      If you provide a listing year (or a "bought around" year), the decoder compares it to the
      year it decoded from the serial and adjusts the confidence accordingly (see above). A
      prefix-definitive format like <code>JP1234</code> (Gibson artist run) always stays
      <code>high</code> regardless of year, because the format itself doesn't encode a year.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Sources</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">
      Every rule in the matcher cites at least two authoritative sources. Authoritative means the
      manufacturer's own documentation, a published reference book, a reputable museum or registry,
      or multiple corroborating expert accounts. Forum posts alone aren't sufficient to change a
      rule — but they're useful signals when they cluster.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
